  "notes": "Bambara (bamanankan), Manding (Mande), Mali. Official Latin orthography (Bamako 1967 alphabet, revised 1982) with the African-reference-alphabet letters ɛ ɔ ɲ ŋ. Seven oral vowels a e ɛ i o ɔ u; length is written by doubling the vowel and nasalisation by a following ⟨n⟩ (both fall out of the base graphemes and are not listed separately). ⟨c⟩ = /t͡ʃ/, ⟨j⟩ = /d͡ʒ/, ⟨y⟩ = /j/. Bambara is a two-tone language (high vs low/mid) but tone is NOT written in the standard orthography, so no tone is emitted here. ⟨w⟩ as the plural suffix is realised [u]; ⟨s⟩ varies [s]~[ʃ]~[z] and ⟨g⟩ [ɡ]~[ɣ] — recorded as allophones.",
